context: France's major upscale department stores are <a0_0><b5_0>Galeries Lafayette and Le Printemps<b5_0/><a0_0/>, which both have flagship stores on Boulevard Haussmann in Paris and branches around the country. The first department store in France, Le Bon Marché in Paris, was founded in <a1_0><b6_0><b7_0>1852<b7_0/><b6_0/><a1_0/> and is now owned by the luxury goods conglomerate <a2_0><b8_0>LVMH<b8_0/><a2_0/>. <a3_0><b9_0>La Samaritaine<b9_0/><a3_0/>, another upscale department store also owned by LVMH, closed in 2005. Mid-range department stores chains also exist in France such as the <a4_0>BHV (Bazar de l'Hotel de Ville)<a4_0/>, part of the same group as Galeries Lafayette.
